Despite Chinese history's overall positive view of intellectuals, the '''Stinking Old Ninth''' ({{Zh|c=臭老九|p=chòu lǎo jiǔ}}) is a Chinese [[dysphemism]] for [[intellectual]]s used at two major points.<ref>{{cite book|last=Li|first=Kwok-sing|title=A glossary of political terms of the People's Republic of China|year=1995|publisher=The Chinese University Press|location=Hong Kong|pages=27–28}}</ref>
The term originated during the [[Yuan Dynasty]] where the [[Mongol]] conquerors identified ten "[[caste]]s" of Chinese: [[Mandarin (bureaucrat)|bureaucrat]]s, [[official]]s, [[Buddhist monk]]s, [[Taoist priest]]s, [[physician]]s, [[worker]]s, [[hunter]]s, [[prostitute]]s, (ninth) [[Confucianism|Confucian]] scholars and finally [[beggar]]s, with only beggars at a status below the intellectuals.
During the [[Cultural Revolution]] the "Nine Black Categories" were: [[Landlord]]s, rich farmers, [[Anti-revolutionary|anti-revolutionaries]], bad influences, [[Right-wing politics|right-wingers]], [[traitor]]s, [[Espionage|spies]], [[capitalist roader]]s and (ninth) [[intellectual]]s. While often attributed to [[Mao Zedong]], in 1977, [[Deng Xiaoping]] argued that it was the [[Gang of Four]] who came up with the phrase and that Mao himself saw intellectuals as having some value in society.<ref>{{cite book|last=Deng|first=Xiaoping|title=Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping, Volume 2|year=1984|publisher=Foreign Language Press|location=Beijing|chapter=Mao Zedong Thought Must be Correctly Understood as an Integral Whole}}</ref>
